Title:
0x33 – Full Windows Offense Pipeline: PEB Walking to Kernel Rootkit (DKOM + Callback Abuse)

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
This post is a code-heavy walkthrough that starts from a simple WinAPI call (MessageBoxA) and builds up a full offensive chain through user-mode evasion and injection techniques into kernel-mode rootkit capabilities. It covers dynamic API resolution (including manual PEB walking and PE export parsing) to avoid static imports and reduce visibility to analysis/hooking. It then demonstrates multiple injection primitives: IAT hooking, process hollowing, classic remote-thread DLL/shellcode injection, ntdll/NTAPI-based injection, and Early Bird APC injection with encrypted payloads (XOR/AES via CryptoAPI). The latter sections move into driver development basics (DriverEntry, IRPs, device objects/symlinks) and rootkit techniques including kernel image-load callbacks for injection, DKOM process/driver hiding, and token stealing for privilege escalation. It also discusses practical constraints like version-dependent EPROCESS offsets and PatchGuard/KPP detection risk. Useful primarily for red teamers, malware developers, and defenders wanting concrete examples of how these primitives chain together.

Technical Focus:
- Manual API resolution via PEB walking and PE export table parsing
- Import Address Table (IAT) hooking
- Process hollowing (CREATE_SUSPENDED, WriteProcessMemory, SetThreadContext/ResumeThread)
- Remote injection variants (CreateRemoteThread, NtCreateThreadEx, QueueUserAPC / Early Bird)
- Payload/string obfuscation and runtime decryption (XOR, AES-256 via CryptoAPI)
- Kernel driver/rootkit primitives (PsSetLoadImageNotifyRoutine, DKOM, ObRegisterCallbacks, token stealing)

Use Cases:
- Build loaders that avoid static imports and common user-mode hooks
- Implement and compare process injection techniques (thread creation vs APC-based)
- Prototype process hollowing for masquerading under legitimate binaries
- Develop a basic Windows kernel driver with user-mode control via IOCTL
- Experiment with kernel-mode persistence/stealth (DKOM unlinking, module hiding)
- Create detections/hunts for PEB-walking, APC injection, image-load callbacks, and DKOM artifacts

Keywords:
Windows internals, PEB, TEB, __readfsdword, GS:[0x60], PE export parsing, GetProcAddress evasion, dynamic API resolution, IAT hooking, IMAGE_IMPORT_DESCRIPTOR, process hollowing, CREATE_SUSPENDED, SetThreadContext, WriteProcessMemory, VirtualAllocEx, CreateRemoteThread, NtAllocateVirtualMemory, NtWriteVirtualMemory, NtCreateThreadEx, QueueUserAPC, Early Bird injection, CryptoAPI, CryptAcquireContextW, CryptDeriveKey, AES-256, kernel driver, DriverEntry, IRP, IoCreateDevice, DeviceIoControl, PsSetLoadImageNotifyRoutine, KeInitializeApc, DKOM, EPROCESS, ActiveProcessLinks, PatchGuard, ObRegisterCallbacks, token stealing, PsInitialSystemProcess